The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-ply cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Home-grown and stable virus
HIV protease is an HIV protein that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV virus division caused by HIV protease, no mature infectious viral particles would occur.
When we switch off the HIV protease, we also disable the proliferation of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists in the press report, which was published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the Scientific Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of connections in which two pairs of the cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease assays tested in the test tube also against its stable (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metalocarbane on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants, which are often ineffective in the use of medicinal products.
