A gradual relaxation
In the Constitution of the country in 1978, China's one-child policy is probably the most controversial provision that has been introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy have to expect huge fines -- up to their triple annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination at their workplace.
Chinese government representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of natural land resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of politics.
