United Nations Group on Emissions Reduction Plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference – which has so far been characterised by wild poses and mutual accusations – once again focused on Friday with the publication of a document, which will record an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrial nations in the near future shouldering the greatest burdens.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has shown both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is due to take place next week, when more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, formulated by a UN working group specifically created for it, rests on the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrial and large emerging countries can limit their carbon emissions and how high should be the upper limit of the global temperature increase that political decision-makers would bear.
The process will provide great flexibility, said John Coequyt, director of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has designed the six-page document, has compiled a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the leading climate protection representative of the UN, Yvo de Boer, has called "the great whole".
It shows the basic outline of a possible agreement whereby industrial nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared with the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also given an impetus to Friday's talks through its assurance to provide USD 3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change - from the masters of floods and droughts to the avoidance of deforestation.
The Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that the talks had scheduled in the last week.
The American climate expert Todd Stern has rejected formulations requiring binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialised countries compared with voluntary reductions for larger emerging countries, if they are not financed by the industrialized nations.
This train announced that the Obama government is driving a harder line with China, as representatives of the Bush government not even two years ago.
