Support for brake manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the anti-lock braking system ABS at the time and as is the case with the stability control ESP, the auxiliary systems for braking in emergency situations must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already required for all newly authorised passenger cars and light small carriers, for the remaining vehicles a standstill period was set until the end of February 2011.
The measures adopted by the European Union aim to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assist is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake manoeuvre, which detects the system by means of the brake strength applied by the driver to the brake pedal.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to hit the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1.100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the brake distance that a car is passing during the braking process.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented every year.
There would be even less accidents - one expects that every fourth accident could be prevented by personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects (via radar or camera) obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system helps him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already unavoidable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes to minimise the damage in this way.
